        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity: 

Observations at mm wavelengths are scarce for the class of E+A galaxies. This is because the post-starburst phase is an event of short duration (less than 1Gyr) and generally these sources should possess a relatively small amount of cold gas in the hypothesis of a merging event that completely exhausted the reservoir. This latter hypothesis is one of the questions addressed in this proposal.

In the few examples observed at mm frequencies in the local Universe, this class of galaxies show a gas mass that can vary from few x 1.0e8Msun up to several 1.0e9Msun with a variety of distributions (ring-like, localized in the nuclear region, more extended configuration). To justify our requested sensitivity we put ourself in the most conservative case as reported for NGC7331. In this E+A galaxy the gas mass originates from several clumps of ~700pc in size with M(H2)=5x1.0e7Msun  each (Tosaky &amp; Shioya 1997). Thus we aim to reach a minimal detectable H2 gas mass of 5x1.0e7Msun in each resolution element (0.4arcsec, or 650pc, i.e. the expected size of the clumps). This  minimal detectable H2 gas mass translates into an rms noise level of 0.3 mJy/beam per 20 km/s (or 7 channels in full spectral resolution of 2.7km/s). With this noise level a 5 sigma detection limit on the integrated line flux is 30mJy km/s. We adopt here a CO-to-H2 conversion factor of alpha=5.0Msun(K km/s pc^2)^-1, typical of the inner regions of nearby galaxies.

Even assuming this conservative scenario and a spatial sampling of 0.4arcsec, we can distinguish among a possible ring-like structure (as in NGC7331 with radii from 2.0 to 4.0kpc), a centrally concentrated emission (e.g., as in NGC4736 and NGC5055), or a more extended distribution. 

In conclusion, we ask for 1.95h on source (or 3.76h total time).

Imaging: 

The maximum recoverable structure in the more extended configuration is 8.6arcsec (14kpc). Since the CO mapping in nearby elliptical galaxies has shown that the disks can extend out to ~10kpc (Young et al. 2008), we  do not risk losing structure on larger scales with the array only.  Thus we do not ask for complementary ACA observations.


Correlator set-up:

The high spectral resolution mode (FDM) will be used in dual polarization mode, giving us 976.6~kHz wide channels over 1.875 GHz bandwidth per baseband. The resulting channel separation is ~2.7km/s. The low resolution mode TDM will be used for the other three base-bands. The total continuum sensitivity in our maps will be better than 17 microJy/beam.

Calibration:

Standard calibrations are appropriate for this project.
Bandpass accuracy: 

The spectral features we intend to observe in this project do not cover a significant fraction of the spectral window and CO(1-0) line is expected to be significantly brighter than its underlying continuum.

Scheduling/time constraints:

none

No special Data rate.

No special constraints.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
