    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>It is fair to say that the mechanism(s) for the rapid shutoff of star formation are not known precisely and a systematic study to clarify it is needed. The amount, distribution, and kinematics of the molecular gas - the fuel of the star formation - can help in solving this issue.
With these observations we propose to complement the expected findings of the scheduled Cycle 1 observations of Zwaan et al. of two HI-rich post-starburst galaxies. We select the well-studied post-starburst galaxy, G515, without HI gas detected but significant 1.4GHz radio continuum emission and strong evidence of variability. Unlike the HI-rich post-starbursts of Zwaan et al., this system probably harbours a weak AGN approaching the end of its duty cycles.
We thus plan to compare the CO(2-1) emission in these two samples to provide a strong initial indication as to the dominating mechanisms of post-starburst galaxies and shed light on how galaxies move from the blue cloud to the red sequence.
</prp:abstract>
